--- body ---
## Context

The 0159 reorg removed `release/` from the repo: engine tooling moved to
`build/` + `docs/`, and submission *records* moved out of the repo to
`papiers/<state>/<track>/`. Several docs still instruct contributors to put new
submission artifacts in `release/`, or point at record files by their old
`release/...` path. These were deliberately left out of the extraction PR
because rewriting them is a workflow redesign, not a mechanical path swap — the
submission-branch *mechanism* itself is in question (see Open question below).

## Relevant files

Process instructions (tell contributors WHERE new submission artifacts go):
- `.agent/runbooks/submission-branch.md` — many `release/...` instructions
- `.agent/runbooks/submission-readiness.md` — checklist items naming `release/`
- `.claude/skills/submission-branch/SKILL.md` — "Add to `release/`: ..."
- `.claude/skills/submission-readiness/SKILL.md` — checklist items naming `release/`
- `.agent/guidelines/coding-guidelines.md:87` — "submissions in `release/`"

Stale record pointers in moved process logs (point at relocated record files):
- `docs/release-journal.md` — cover-letter / decision-letter / AI-statement paths
- `docs/rdj-submission-checklist.md` — CoverLetter / journal paths
- `docs/revision-runbook.md:136` — `release/revision-diff/...` example path

## Actions
1. Decide the new submission convention (see Open question), then rewrite the
   runbooks + submission skills to instruct `papiers/<state>/<track>/` instead
   of `release/`.
2. Update the stale record pointers in `docs/release-journal.md`,
   `docs/rdj-submission-checklist.md`, and the `docs/revision-runbook.md`
   example to the papiers track paths (or describe by track name if a relative
   path would break after the Phase-2 engine move to projets/).
3. Update `.agent/guidelines/coding-guidelines.md:87`.

## Open question (resolve first)
With records now outside the repo (untracked `papiers/`), does the
`submission-branch` mechanism — protected branches carrying `release/` artifacts
— still make sense? Options: (a) keep submission branches for the manuscript
*source* freeze, records go to papiers; (b) retire submission branches entirely;
(c) something else. This is the author's call and drives the doc rewrite.

## Test
- Grep ratchet: after the rewrite, `git grep -n "release/" -- '.agent' '.claude/skills' 'docs'`
  returns 0 process-instruction hits (historical log entries excepted, if any
  are intentionally preserved).

## Verification
- [ ] Runbooks + submission skills name `papiers/<state>/<track>/`, not `release/`
- [ ] Stale record pointers in docs/ updated or described by track
- [ ] Open question resolved and reflected in the submission-branch mechanism docs
- [ ] `make check` green

## Invariants
- Do not rewrite dated historical log *events* into fiction — update pointers
  only, preserve the record of what happened when.

## Exit criteria
- Submission workflow docs/skills consistent with the post-0159 layout; no
  process instruction still points at `release/`.
